</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="271" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,727,1977]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">
Traditionally, the species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mathews &amp; Iredale" authorityYear="1915" box="[472,603,727,753]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[472,603,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Calonectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were usually placed in the same genus as the other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brisson" authorityYear="1760" box="[1195,1288,727,753]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Puffinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1195,1288,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Puffinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shearwaters; the former genus came to be widely recognized only about 50 years after its description, based mostly on the work of 
<bibRefCitation author="Kuroda, N. H." box="[184,353,798,825]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" refId="ref19713" refString="Kuroda, N. H. (1954) On the Classification and Phylogeny of the Order Tubinares, Particularly the Shearwaters (Puffinus), with Special Considerations on their Osteology and Habit Differentiation. N. H. Kuroda, Tokyo, 179 pp." type="book" year="1954">Kuroda (1954)</bibRefCitation>
(
<emphasis box="[372,412,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">e.g.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Alexander, W. B. &amp; Falla, R. A. &amp; Jouanin, C. &amp; Murphy, R. C. &amp; Salomonsen, F. &amp; Voous, K. H. &amp; Watson, G. E. &amp; Bourne, W. R. P. &amp; Fleming, C. A. &amp; Kuroda, N. H. &amp; Rowan, M. K. &amp; Serventy, D. L. &amp; Tickell, W. L. N. &amp; Warham, J. &amp; Winterbottom, J. M." box="[422,677,798,825]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="401 - 405" refId="ref17957" refString="Alexander, W. B., Falla, R. A., Jouanin, C., Murphy, R. C., Salomonsen, F., Voous, K. H., Watson, G. E., Bourne, W. R. P., Fleming, C. A., Kuroda, N. H., Rowan, M. K., Serventy, D. L., Tickell, W. L. N., Warham, J. &amp; Winterbottom, J. M. (1965) The families andgenera of petrels and their names. Ibis, 107 (3), 401 - 405. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1474 - 919 X. 1965. tb 07326. x" type="journal article" year="1965">
Alexander 
<emphasis box="[548,600,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al</emphasis>
. 1965
</bibRefCitation>
). In the final phylogenetic hypothesis of our study, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mathews &amp; Iredale" authorityYear="1915" box="[1277,1408,799,825]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1277,1408,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Calonectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is supported by eight unambiguous synapomorphies, such as the 
<emphasis box="[851,1075,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">condylus occipitalis</emphasis>
nonvisible in lateral view of the skull; the presence of a thin osseous 
<emphasis box="[560,638,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">lamina</emphasis>
in 
<emphasis box="[673,926,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">apertura nasalis ossea</emphasis>
, which is shared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Streets" authorityYear="1877" box="[1177,1389,871,897]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Puffinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nativitatis">
<emphasis box="[1177,1389,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Puffinus nativitatis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,260,907,933]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Puffinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="huttoni">
<emphasis box="[151,260,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">P. huttoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and the elliptical shaft of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chang &amp; Ren" authorityYear="2013" box="[564,660,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Endomychidae" genus="Humerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[564,660,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">humerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, not flattened as in other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brisson" authorityYear="1760" box="[1070,1163,907,933]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Puffinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1070,1163,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Puffinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[1180,1295,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">sensu lato</emphasis>
) (characters 24, 34, and 69, respectively); all three of these were also cited by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kuroda, N. H." box="[915,1086,942,969]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" refId="ref19713" refString="Kuroda, N. H. (1954) On the Classification and Phylogeny of the Order Tubinares, Particularly the Shearwaters (Puffinus), with Special Considerations on their Osteology and Habit Differentiation. N. H. Kuroda, Tokyo, 179 pp." type="book" year="1954">Kuroda (1954)</bibRefCitation>
. The monophyly of the group, corroborated herein, has also been recovered by previous molecular-based studies, despite the different taxonomic treatments given to the terminal taxa (
<emphasis box="[581,621,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">e.g.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Nunn, G. B. &amp; Stanley, S. E." box="[631,885,1015,1041]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="1360 - 1371" refId="ref20468" refString="Nunn, G. B. &amp; Stanley, S. E. (1998) Body size effects and rates of cytochrome b evolution in tube-nosed seabirds. Molecular Biology and Evolution, 15 (10), 1360 - 1371. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / oxfordjournals. molbev. a 025864" type="journal article" year="1998">Nunn &amp; Stanley 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Austin, J. J. &amp; Bretagnolle, V. &amp; Pasquet, E." box="[897,1108,1015,1041]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="847 - 864" refId="ref18154" refString="Austin, J. J., Bretagnolle, V. &amp; Pasquet, E. (2004) A global molecular phylogeny of the small Puffinus shearwaters and implications for systematics of the Little-Audubon's shearwater complex. The Auk, 121 (3), 847 - 864. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / auk / 121.3.847" type="journal article" year="2004">
Austin 
<emphasis box="[981,1039,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Penhallurick, J. &amp; Wink, W." box="[1121,1432,1015,1041]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="125 - 147" refId="ref20653" refString="Penhallurick, J. &amp; Wink, W. (2004) Analysis of the taxonomy and nomenclature of the Procellariiformes based on complete nucleotide sequences of the mitochondrial cytochrome b gene. Emu, 104 (2), 125 - 147. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / MU 01060" type="journal article" year="2004">Penhallurick &amp; Wink 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Welch, A. J. &amp; Olson, S. L. &amp; Fleischer, R. C." box="[151,353,1051,1077]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="494 - 505" refId="ref21818" refString="Welch, A. J., Olson, S. L. &amp; Fleischer, R. C. (2014) Phylogenetic relationships of the extinct St Helena petrel, Pterodroma rupinarum Olson, 1975 (Procellariiformes: Procellariidae), based on ancient DNA. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 170 (3), 494 - 505. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zoj. 12078" type="journal article" year="2014">
Welch 
<emphasis box="[229,285,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,727,1977]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">
In our phylogenetic analysis, relationships within the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mathews &amp; Iredale" authorityYear="1915" box="[891,1022,1087,1113]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[891,1022,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Calonectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were almost entirely established by synapomorphies from continuous characters, such as the lengths of wing bones (
<emphasis box="[1061,1101,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">e.g.</emphasis>
characters 9, 10, 11, and 12), and received high support (RBS ≥ 70 for all nodes). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[752,1000,1159,1185]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[752,1000,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Calonectris diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[1057,1182,1159,1185]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[1057,1182,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are sister taxa to each other, sharing seven synapomorphies from continuous characters. Most molecular phylogenies have included only one or two species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mathews &amp; Iredale" authorityYear="1915" box="[390,521,1231,1257]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[390,521,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Calonectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as terminal taxa. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ramirez, O. &amp; Illera, J. C. &amp; Rando, J. C. &amp; Gonzalez-Solis, J. &amp; Alcover, J. A. &amp; Lalueza-Fox, C." box="[715,952,1231,1257]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="16072" refId="ref20853" refString="Ramirez, O., Illera, J. C., Rando, J. C., Gonzalez-Solis, J., Alcover, J. A. &amp; Lalueza-Fox, C. (2010) Ancient DNA of the extinct Lava Shearwater (Puffinus olsoni) from the Canary Islands reveals incipient differentiation within the P. puffinus complex. Plos One, 5 (12), e 16072. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0016072" type="journal article" year="2010">
Ramirez 
<emphasis box="[817,872,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al.</emphasis>
(2010)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Tennyson, A. J. D. &amp; Shepherd, L. D." box="[1004,1334,1231,1257]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="379 - 384" refId="ref21622" refString="Tennyson, A. J. D. &amp; Shepherd, L. D. (2017) DNA reveals the relationships of the extinct Scarlett's Shearwater Puffinus spelaeus (Procellariiformes: Procellariidae). Journal of Ornithology, 158, 379 - 384. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10336 - 016 - 1416 - 5" type="journal article" year="2017">Tennyson &amp; Shepherd (2017)</bibRefCitation>
included only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[208,350,1267,1293]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[208,350,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whereas some other studies also sequenced 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1836" box="[854,1012,1267,1293]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomelas">
<emphasis box="[854,1012,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. leucomelas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[1029,1069,1267,1292]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">e.g.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Nunn, G. B. &amp; Stanley, S. E." box="[1076,1324,1267,1293]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="1360 - 1371" refId="ref20468" refString="Nunn, G. B. &amp; Stanley, S. E. (1998) Body size effects and rates of cytochrome b evolution in tube-nosed seabirds. Molecular Biology and Evolution, 15 (10), 1360 - 1371. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / oxfordjournals. molbev. a 025864" type="journal article" year="1998">Nunn &amp; Stanley 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Austin, J. J. &amp; Bretagnolle, V. &amp; Pasquet, E." pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="847 - 864" refId="ref18154" refString="Austin, J. J., Bretagnolle, V. &amp; Pasquet, E. (2004) A global molecular phylogeny of the small Puffinus shearwaters and implications for systematics of the Little-Audubon's shearwater complex. The Auk, 121 (3), 847 - 864. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / auk / 121.3.847" type="journal article" year="2004">
Austin 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pyle, P. &amp; Welch, A. J. &amp; Fleischer, R. C." box="[257,433,1303,1329]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="518 - 527" refId="ref20791" refString="Pyle, P., Welch, A. J. &amp; Fleischer, R. C. (2011) A new species of shearwater (Puffinus) recorded from Midway Atoll, northwestern Hawaiian Islands. The Condor, 113 (3), 518 - 527. https: // doi. org / 10.1525 / cond. 2011.100117" type="journal article" year="2011">
Pyle 
<emphasis box="[313,369,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Welch, A. J. &amp; Olson, S. L. &amp; Fleischer, R. C." box="[443,644,1303,1329]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="494 - 505" refId="ref21818" refString="Welch, A. J., Olson, S. L. &amp; Fleischer, R. C. (2014) Phylogenetic relationships of the extinct St Helena petrel, Pterodroma rupinarum Olson, 1975 (Procellariiformes: Procellariidae), based on ancient DNA. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 170 (3), 494 - 505. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zoj. 12078" type="journal article" year="2014">
Welch 
<emphasis box="[521,577,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Heidrich, P. &amp; Amengual, J. &amp; Wink, M." box="[661,904,1303,1329]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="145 - 170" refId="ref19561" refString="Heidrich, P., Amengual, J. &amp; Wink, M. (1998) Phylogenetic relationships in Mediterranean and North Atlantic Puffinus shearwaters (Aves: Procellariidae) based on nucleotide sequences of mtDNA. Biochemical Systematics and Ecology, 26 (2), 145 - 170. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0305 - 1978 (97) 00085 - 9" type="journal article" year="1998">
Heidrich 
<emphasis box="[766,822,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al.</emphasis>
(1998)
</bibRefCitation>
, when assessing relationships of Mediterranean and North Atlantic shearwaters through mtDNA, used both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[839,983,1339,1365]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[839,983,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[1043,1169,1339,1365]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[1043,1169,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[1292,1383,1339,1365]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[1292,1383,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was considered a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[460,603,1375,1401]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[460,603,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the present study, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1836" box="[855,1015,1375,1401]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomelas">
<emphasis box="[855,1015,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. leucomelas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appeared as sister to (
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[1270,1412,1375,1401]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[1270,1412,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[151,275,1411,1437]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[151,275,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), forming a clade supported by eleven synapomorphies (
<emphasis box="[917,952,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">i.e.</emphasis>
, nine from continuous characters, plus one unambiguous and one ambiguous). 
<bibRefCitation author="Penhallurick, J. &amp; Wink, W." box="[550,870,1447,1473]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="125 - 147" refId="ref20653" refString="Penhallurick, J. &amp; Wink, W. (2004) Analysis of the taxonomy and nomenclature of the Procellariiformes based on complete nucleotide sequences of the mitochondrial cytochrome b gene. Emu, 104 (2), 125 - 147. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / MU 01060" type="journal article" year="2004">Penhallurick &amp; Wink (2004)</bibRefCitation>
, who included three of four species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mathews &amp; Iredale" authorityYear="1915" box="[1299,1430,1447,1473]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1299,1430,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Calonectris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, found 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1836" box="[223,382,1483,1509]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomelas">
<emphasis box="[223,382,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. leucomelas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be sister to (
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[555,696,1483,1509]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[555,696,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[726,849,1483,1509]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[726,849,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the same relationship we present herein. However, these authors suggested that these two taxa should continue to be treated as subspecies, whereas most of the recent literature considers 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[427,569,1555,1581]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[427,569,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[624,749,1555,1581]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[624,749,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be valid species (
<emphasis box="[980,1015,1555,1580]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">i.e.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Sangster, G. &amp; Collinson, J. M. &amp; Crochet, P. - A. &amp; Knox, A. G. &amp; Parkin, D. T. &amp; Votier, S. C." box="[1022,1250,1555,1581]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="874 - 883" refId="ref21078" refString="Sangster, G., Collinson, J. M., Crochet, P. - A., Knox, A. G., Parkin, D. T. &amp; Votier, S. C. (2012) Taxonomic recommendations for British birds: eighth report. Ibis, 154 (4), 874 - 883. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1474 - 919 X. 2012.01273. x" type="journal article" year="2012">
Sangster 
<emphasis box="[1126,1183,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gill, F. &amp; Donsker, D. &amp; Rasmussen, P." pageId="28" pageNumber="271" refId="ref18912" refString="Gill, F., Donsker, D. &amp; Rasmussen, P. (Eds) (2019) IOC World Bird List (v 10.2). Available from: https: // www. worldbirdnames. org / ioc-lists / master-list- 2 / (accessed 12 Jan 2021)" type="url" year="2019">Gill &amp; Donsker 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,727,1977]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">
Together with 
<emphasis box="[364,681,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1836" box="[364,527,1627,1653]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomelas">C. leucomelas</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[539,681,1627,1653]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">C. diomedea</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[744,869,1627,1653]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[744,869,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the present study has also included 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Oustalet" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[1286,1429,1627,1653]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis box="[1286,1429,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which was found to be sister to (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1836" box="[529,690,1663,1689]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomelas">
<emphasis box="[529,690,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. leucomelas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[708,852,1663,1689]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[708,852,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[885,1011,1663,1689]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[885,1011,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)). This result contrasts with the relationship proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gomez-Diaz, E. &amp; Gonzalez-Solis, J. &amp; Peinado, M. A. &amp; Page, R. D. M." box="[395,677,1699,1725]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="322 - 332" refId="ref19439" refString="Gomez-Diaz, E., Gonzalez-Solis, J., Peinado, M. A. &amp; Page, R. D. M. (2006) Phylogeography of the Calonectris shearwaters using molecular and morphometric data. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 41 (2), 322 - 332. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2006.05.006" type="journal article" year="2006">
Gómez-Díaz 
<emphasis box="[545,595,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al</emphasis>
. (2006
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gomez-Diaz, E. &amp; Gonzalez-Solis, J. &amp; Peinado, M. A." box="[689,749,1699,1725]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="197 - 209" refId="ref19375" refString="Gomez-Diaz, E., Gonzalez-Solis, J. &amp; Peinado, M. A. (2009) Population structure in a highly pelagic seabird, the Cory's Shearwater Calonectris diomedea: an examination of genetics, morphology and ecology. Marine Ecology Progress Series, 382, 197 - 209. https: // doi. org / 10.3354 / meps 07974" type="journal article" year="2009">2009</bibRefCitation>
), who also included all four species in their phylogeographic analyses based on the cytochrome 
<emphasis box="[554,568,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">b</emphasis>
gene. According to these authors, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[974,1119,1735,1761]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[974,1119,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Oustalet" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[1179,1324,1735,1761]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis box="[1179,1324,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are more closely related to each other than either is to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[666,791,1771,1797]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[666,791,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1836" box="[855,1015,1771,1797]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomelas">
<emphasis box="[855,1015,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. leucomelas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sister to all other 
<taxonomicName class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1250,1381,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Calonectris</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
Nonetheless, when discussing only the biometric structure of 
<taxonomicName box="[910,1133,1807,1833]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[910,1041,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">Calonectris</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gomez-Diaz, E. &amp; Gonzalez-Solis, J. &amp; Peinado, M. A. &amp; Page, R. D. M." box="[1145,1436,1807,1834]" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" pagination="322 - 332" refId="ref19439" refString="Gomez-Diaz, E., Gonzalez-Solis, J., Peinado, M. A. &amp; Page, R. D. M. (2006) Phylogeography of the Calonectris shearwaters using molecular and morphometric data. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 41 (2), 322 - 332. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2006.05.006" type="journal article" year="2006">
Gómez-Díaz 
<emphasis box="[1296,1347,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">et al</emphasis>
. (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
acknowledged the similarity of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1769" box="[515,659,1843,1869]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="diomedea">
<emphasis box="[515,659,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. diomedea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cory" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[716,841,1843,1869]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[716,841,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the largest species that they included. According to them, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1836" box="[220,378,1879,1905]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomelas">
<emphasis box="[220,378,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. leucomelas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Oustalet" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[431,573,1879,1905]" class="Aves" family="Procellariidae" genus="Calonectris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Procellariiformes" pageId="28" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edwardsii">
<emphasis box="[431,573,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="271">C. edwardsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are, respectively, the medium-sized and the smallest species of the genus. As mentioned before, the relationship proposed herein was mostly based on synapomorphies from continuous characters, which can explain the apparent clustering by body size measurements.
</paragraph>
